                    <msContents>
                        
                        <summary>
                            <seg type="para"> This quire is part of a collection of fragments bought by Cambridge University Library from  
                                Constantin von Tischendorf's heirs in 1876. It contains a <title> Fragment from a treatise on the Holy Spirit against the Latins</title>. 
                                The text is written by an anonymous scribe, whose hand is also present in two other fragments 
                                in Tischendorf's collection, <bibl subtype="internal" type="MS"> 
                           <ref target="http://cudl.lib.cam.ac.uk/view/MS-ADD-01880-00013">Cambridge, University Library, Add. 1880.13</ref>
                        </bibl> and 
                                <bibl subtype="internal" type="MS"> 
                           <ref target="http://cudl.lib.cam.ac.uk/view/MS-ADD-01880-00016">Cambridge, University Library, Add. 1880.16</ref>
                        </bibl>, which, together with <bibl subtype="internal" type="MS"> Cambridge, University Library, Add. 1880.17</bibl>, derive from a single manuscript. 
                                Manuscripts Add. 1880.15, which bears a text related to the one contained in Add. 1880.13, 
                                and Add. 1880.16 (George Koressios's <hi rend="italic">Dialogue with a Latin teacher</hi>),  
                                may also have originally been part of this book.</seg> 
                            <seg type="para">Dr Erika Elia</seg>
                        </summary>
                        
                        <textLang mainLang="grc" otherLangs="la">Greek and Latin</textLang>
                        
                        <msItem n="1"> 
                            <!--<locus from="1r" to="5v">ff. 1r-5v</locus>-->
                            <title xml:lang="en"> Fragment of a treatise on the Holy Spirit against the Latins</title>
                            <incipit defective="true">
                        <locus from="1r" to="1r"> f. 1r</locus> 
                        <gap> </gap>σιν καὶ ἰδίως ἐκπόρευσιν ἐνεργητικήν τε καὶ παθητικήν</incipit>
                            <explicit defective="true">
                        <locus from="5v" to="5v"> f. 5v</locus> ἔχει δὲ τὸ κτίζειν, τὸ δημιουργεῖν, τὸ ἀίδιον, τὸ εἶναι παντοκρά<gap/>
                     </explicit>
                            <note> The text cites Anastasius, Athanasius, Basil, Cyril, John Chrysostom,
                                Dionysius the Areopagite, Gregory, John Damascene, Justin Martyr and
                                Theodoretus</note>
                            <note> This portion of text is present in <bibl subtype="external" type="MS">
                           <ref target="https://www.loc.gov/item/00279383059-ms/"> 
                                Sinai, Saint Catherine Monastery, MS gr. 1787</ref>
                        </bibl>, ff. 291r l. 15-293r l. 3; in the catalogue by V. Benešević  
                                (<hi rend="italic"> Catalogus Codicum Manuscriptorum Graecorum qui in monasterio Sanctae Catherinae in monte Sina asservantur</hi>, III.1, 
                                St. Petersburg 1917 [reprint Hildesheim 1965], p. 196), this portion of text is comprised in George Koressios's <hi rend="italic">Dialogue with a Latin teacher</hi>, 
                                however this part is not present in the printed edition of the text (ed. by N. Metaxas, presumably in Constantinople around 1627
                               <bibl> Τοῦ μακαριωτάτου πατρὸς ἡμῶν Μελετίου Ἀρχιεπισκόπου Ἀλεξανδρείας, Λιβύης, Πενταπόλεως, 
                                    Αἰθιωπίας, καὶ πάσης γῆς Αἰγύπτου Περὶ τῆς ἀρχῆς τοῦ πᾶπα ὡς ἐν εἴδει έπιστολῶν, [Constantinople] [1627?]</bibl>)</note>
                        </msItem>
                        
                    </msContents>
                    
